  <h2>Planting your succulent</h2>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col col-lg-9">
      <p>
        So you've got your first succulent from the gardening center, now what? The first thing you want to do is take it out of the ugly plastic container and put it in something more aesthetic!
        When picking your pot there are two things you should consider:
        <ol>
          <strong><li>Planters without draining holes</li></strong>
            <ul>
              <li>If your planter doesn't have drain holes, you must make sure to create a draining layer with pebbles. That way your roots don't remain soaked when watering</li>
              <li>It's essential to use well draining soil to prevent the soil getting soaked</li>
              <li>As much as plants like water, succulents don't need that much</li>
            </ul>
          <strong><li>Really big planters</li></strong>
            <ul>
              <li>You should avoid using large planters because the roots will spread out before the succulent can catch up</li>
            </ul>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        Now that you have your planter ready with soil, time to unroot your succulent from the plastic pot. You can do this by squeezing
        the sides of the plastic pot to free the succulent. Make sure to clean off the excess soil on the plant's roots. Next, make a hole
        in your nice succulent planter, then put the succulent in. Make sure to pat the soil down. Congrats, you planted your first succulent.
      </p>
